  "prompt": "Cost for 1kg of A is 260 USD and 1kg of B is 380. AB is made by mixing A and B. If 1kg of AB costs 300, what was the ratio that A and B has mixed?",
  "response": "Let \\( x \\) be the amount of A in kg and \\( y \\) be the amount of B in kg used to create 1 kg of AB. \n\nGiven that:\n\n1. The cost of 1 kg of A is $260.\n2. The cost of 1 kg of B is $380.\n3. The cost of 1 kg of AB is $300.\n\nThe total cost of the mixture can be expressed as:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Cost of AB} = \\text{Cost of A} + \\text{Cost of B}\n\\]\n\nSince we want to mix A and B such that the total weight is 1 kg, we have:\n\n\\[\nx + y = 1\n\\]\n\nThe cost of the mixture can also be expressed as:\n\n\\[\n260x + 380y = 300\n\\]\n\nNow, we can solve these equations step by step.\n\nFrom the first equation, we can express \\( y \\) in terms of \\( x \\):\n\n\\[\ny = 1 - x\n\\]\n\nSubstituting \\( y \\) into the cost equation gives:\n\n\\[\n260x + 380(1 - x) = 300\n\\]\n\nExpanding this:\n\n\\[\n260x + 380 - 380x = 300\n\\]\n\nCombining like terms gives:\n\n\\[\n-120x + 380 = 300\n\\]\n\nSubtracting 380 from both sides:\n\n\\[\n-120x = 300 - 380\n\\]\n\\[\n-120x = -80\n\\]\n\nDividing both sides by -120:\n\n\\[\nx = \\frac{-80}{-120} = \\frac{2}{3}\n\\]\n\nNow, substituting \\( x \\) back into the equation for \\( y \\):\n\n\\[\ny = 1 - x = 1 - \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{1}{3}\n\\]\n\nSo the ratio of A to B is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Ratio of A to B} = \\frac{x}{y} = \\frac{\\frac{2}{3}}{\\frac{1}{3}} = 2:1\n\\]\n\nThus, the ratio in which A and B are mixed is \\( \\boxed{2:1} \\).",
